<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920102-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>920102-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Group Ranks California   First on Worker Safety</HL><DATE>01/02/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>ARKANSAS (AR)CALIFORNIA (CA)ILLINOIS (IL)NEW JERSEY (NJ)NEW MEXICO (NM)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WYOMING (WY)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- California ranked first and Arkansas last inworker-safety ratings issued by the National Safe WorkplaceInstitute, an advocacy group.   The Chicago-based group ranked the 50 states according totheir hazard-prevention, enforcement and workers compensationprograms. It considered, among other things, whether theyrequire occupational-disease reporting by doctors, and itlooked at states' toxics-reduction laws, the fines theyimpose for catastrophic accidents, and the compensation theyprovide injured or diseased workers.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;State government has an important -- but largelyunrecognized -- role in promoting safer and healthierworkplaces,&quot; the institute said. It gave California 81 pointson a scale with a possible perfect score of 116. New Jerseywas second with 80 points, and Illinois and New York weretied for third, with 76 points.   Arkansas ranked at the bottom with 11 points. Second andthird worst, respectively, were Wyoming, 12 points, and NewMexico, 14 points.   California, New Mexico and Wyoming have been givenjurisdiction over occupational safety and health enforcementby the federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration.OSHA directly regulates workplace health and safety inArkansas, Illinois, New Jersey and New York. But all thestates control many of the programs involved in the ratingsystem.</TEXT></DOC>